description:
## Severity
Major
## Dimension
security
## Location
src/tui/app.rs:164-200
## Violation
expand_file_refs follows the canonicalize-then-read pattern, which is a classic TOCTOU (time-of-check-to-time-of-use) race:

```rust
match std::fs::canonicalize(&resolved) {
    Ok(canonical) => {
        if !canonical.starts_with(&cwd) {
            replacements.push((..., "[File outside project directory: ...]"));
            continue;
        }
        match std::fs::read_to_string(&canonical) {  // <-- different read than the canonicalize
            Ok(content) => { ... }
        }
    }
    ...
}
```

Between the canonicalize() and the read_to_string(), an attacker (or untrusted parallel process) can replace `canonical` with a symlink to anywhere on disk — e.g., /etc/shadow, ~/.ssh/id_rsa, ~/.claude/.credentials.json. The check that `canonical.starts_with(&cwd)` runs on the resolved path returned by canonicalize, but read_to_string follows symlinks at the (later) point of actual read.

Additionally, `canonical.starts_with(&cwd)` allows the parent of cwd to be a prefix: if cwd is `/home/user/project` and a sibling file is at `/home/user/projectXXX/secret`, the check still passes because PathBuf::starts_with is path-component-aware ONLY if both paths use canonical separators — it does NOT account for cases like `/home/user/project-stuff` where the prefix string-matches but is a sibling directory. Actually `Path::starts_with` IS component-aware, so this specific case is OK; the TOCTOU above is the real defect.

The .. check on line 153-162 is also bypassable via symlinks pointing outside the project — `ln -s ../../etc/passwd evil` in cwd, then `@evil` resolves with no `..` components in `resolved` but canonicalize returns `/etc/passwd`. The current code DOES then catch this via the starts_with check, but only because canonicalize was just called — between that and read_to_string the symlink can flip.

## Mandated refactor
Use `File::open(&canonical)` which returns a file descriptor pinned to the inode at open time, then read from that descriptor. The TOCTOU window closes because subsequent symlink flips don't affect an already-open fd. Or use `nix::fcntl::openat` with O_NOFOLLOW for stricter symlink rejection.

```rust
match std::fs::File::open(&canonical) {
    Ok(mut f) => {
        // Re-stat via the fd to confirm it's still within cwd
        let metadata = f.metadata().ok();
        // ... validation
        let mut content = String::new();
        f.read_to_string(&mut content).ok();
        ...
    }
    Err(_) => { ... }
}
```

Reject symlinks entirely if the project requires it.

